li.p:
 We can write a parametric description for the solution
	space to the homogeneous equation as

	  \xvec =
	  \left[\begin{array}{r}
	  x_1 \\ 2x_4 - 3x_6 \\ -x_4-4x_6 \\ x_4 \\ x_6 \\ x_6
	  \end{array}\right]
	  =
	  x_1
	  \left[\begin{array}{r}
	  1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\
	  \end{array}\right]
	  +x_4
	  \left[\begin{array}{r}
	  0 \\ 2 \\ -1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\
	  \end{array}\right] + x_6
	  \left[\begin{array}{r}
	  0 \\ -3 \\ -4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 1
	  \end{array}\right]\text{.}

	Therefore, a basis for \nul(A) is

	  \left[\begin{array}{r}
	  1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\
	  \end{array}\right],
	  \left[\begin{array}{r}
	  0 \\ 2 \\ -1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\
	  \end{array}\right],
	  \left[\begin{array}{r}
	  0 \\ -3 \\ -4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 1
	  \end{array}\right]\text{.}

We have
A = \left[\begin{array}{rr} 2 \amp -4 \\ -1 \amp 2 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr} 1 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{,}
which shows that \xvec=x_2\twovec{2}{1} describes the solution space to the homogeneous equation.
